                    rdfs:label "data granularity"@en ;
                    dp:embedding_label "has data granularity"@en .


###  https://www.michaeldebellis.com/dp/embedding_label
dp:embedding_label rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty ;
                   rdfs:label "embedding label"@en ;
                   skos:definition "This property is used to define an additional label to be used when generating text strings for dp:embedding_note. It is for cases (e.g., dcat:catalog) where the defined label won't yield an understandable string. E.g., for dcat:catalog we want a string like \"Catalog1 has sub-catalog Catalog1_Sub\" but the defined label would give: \"Catalog1 catalog Catalog1_Sub\" so we define the string: \"has sub-catalog\" for dp:embedding_label on dcat:catalog."@en ;
                   dp:embedding_note "embedding label has definition This property is used to define an additional label to be used when generating text strings for dp:embedding_note. It is for cases (e.g., dcat:catalog) where the defined label won't yield an understandable string. E.g., for dcat:catalog we want a string like \"Catalog1 has sub-catalog Catalog1_Sub\" but the defined label would give: \"Catalog1 catalog Catalog1_Sub\" so we define the string: \"has sub-catalog\" for dp:embedding_label on dcat:catalog."@en .


###  https://www.michaeldebellis.com/dp/embedding_note
dp:embedding_note rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty ;
                  rdfs:label "embedding note"@en ;
                  skos:definition """This property contains a string generated by a Python program. The program takes basic knowledge that is defined in the structure of a knowledge graph based on OWL and generates English text string. The reason to do this is that in a RAG architecture, the LLM doesn't have access to the information in the knowledge graph. This takes that knowledge and encodes it as strings that the LLM can understand. Right now it generates three kinds of strings:
1) Instance strings. For most Individuals find the rdf:type of each individual (before running the reasoner so just the essential type) using the pattern: 
\"<Instance Label> is an instance of <class label>
2) For the most important classes generate strings such as: 
\"<Class Label> is a subclass of <super-class label>\"
3) For the most important propertie (p): match all triples of the form:
\"?subject p ?object\". Then generate strings using the pattern:
\"<Subject Label>  <property label>  <Object label>\"

The properties and classes used to generate the strings are in files called embedding_classes.txt and embedding_properties.txt. 

Also, for many annotation and datatype properties where the labels don't follow the \"has foo\" or \"is foo of\" convention we define an embedding_label. E.g., the property dcat:catalog points from an instance of Catalog to a sub-catalog. So its embedding label is: \"has sub-catalog\"  This is done to maintain consistency with the vocabularies that we reuse such as DCAT and PROV."""@en ;
                  dp:embedding_note """embedding note has definition This property contains a string generated by a Python program. The program takes basic knowledge that is defined in the structure of a knowledge graph based on OWL and generates English text string. The reason to do this is that in a RAG architecture, the LLM doesn't have access to the information in the knowledge graph. This takes that knowledge and encodes it as strings that the LLM can understand. Right now it generates three kinds of strings:
1) Instance strings. For most Individuals find the rdf:type of each individual (before running the reasoner so just the essential type) using the pattern: 
\"<Instance Label> is an instance of <class label>
2) For the most important classes generate strings such as: 
\"<Class Label> is a subclass of <super-class label>\"
3) For the most important propertie (p): match all triples of the form:
\"?subject p ?object\". Then generate strings using the pattern:
\"<Subject Label>  <property label>  <Object label>\"

The properties and classes used to generate the strings are in files called embedding_classes.txt and embedding_properties.txt. 

Also, for many annotation and datatype properties where the labels don't follow the \"has foo\" or \"is foo of\" convention we define an embedding_label. E.g., the property dcat:catalog points from an instance of Catalog to a sub-catalog. So its embedding label is: \"has sub-catalog\"  This is done to maintain consistency with the vocabularies that we reuse such as DCAT and PROV."""@en .


###  https://www.michaeldebellis.com/dp/intended_use
dp:intended_use rdf:type owl:AnnotationProperty ;
                rdfs:label "intended use"@en ;
                dp:embedding_label "has intended use"@en .


